extension structure：
.specify/
└── extensions/
    └── my-ext/
        ├── manifest.yml           //important
        ├── my-ext-config.yml
        ├── templates/
        └── commands/
            └── testplan.md

my-ext-config.yml is optional, in reality the structure would be:
.specify/extensions/my-ext/
        ├── extension.yml           
        ├── templates/
        └── commands/

a hook is a mechanism that lets software automatically run some additional logic when a specifc event occurs.
a complementary extension is an extension that works alongside another extension or the core SpecKit workflow. （是对其它extension或者core SpecKit workflow的一个补充）


Extension Configuration:
step 5:
$ cd <my-project>
$ specify extension add --dev ../spec-kit-practice/my-extension

Manifest Schema Reference section tells how to write manifest.yml; Command File Format section tells how to write testplan.md
manifest: tells the system what commands we have; command file: tells the system how to execute the commands


Configuration Files：
to separate configuration from application behaviours

.extensionignore files: similar to .gitignore, specify which files are not included in the extension package which would be sent to users for installation
eg. 
my-ext/
├── manifest.yml
├── commands/
├── templates/
├── README.md
├── .git/
├── .vscode/
├── test/
├── logs/
└── .extensionignore

commands/ ✅ 
manifest.yml ✅ 
templates/ ✅ 
other files would be NOT sent to users


Distribution:
it refers to how an extension, preset, workflow or bundle is packaged and shared with users, it's about getting your extension from the developers to other users
for example, if you create a testing extension spec-kit-test, you can distribute it through:
1. a spec-kit catalog
2. a git repo
3. a zip/package url
4. company's private catalog
users can install it with commands such as:
$ specify extension add spec-kit-test


